ice? -- tEssays. Restoring Indigenous Mindfulness within the Commons of Human Consciousness -- tEssays. Reading Records with Estella Leopold -- tEssays. How to Be Better Ancestors -- tC. Interview: Wes Jackson -- tD. Poem: Omoiyare -- tV. Earthly Other-than- human beings are our ancestors, too -- tA. Poem: LEAF -- tB. Essays -- tEssay. The City Bleeds Out (Reflections on Lake Michigan) -- tEssay. I Want the Earth to Know Me as a Friend -- tEssay. The Apple Tree -- tEssay. Humus -- tEssay. Building Good Soil -- tC. Interview: Vandana Shiva -- tD. Poem: Your Inheritance -- tVI. Seventh Fire -- tA. Poem: Time Traveler -- tB. Essays -- tEssay. Seeds -- tEssay. Onëö (Word for Corn in Seneca) -- tEssay. Landing -- tEssay. Regenerative -- tEssay. Nourishing -- tEssay. Light -- tC. Interview: Ilarion Merculieff -- tD. Poem: Lost in the Milky Way -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tAbout the Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAs we face an ever-more-fragmented world, What Kind of Ancestor Do You Want to Be? demands a return to the force of lineage—to spiritual, social, and ecological connections across time. It sparks a myriad of ageless-yet-urgent questions: How will I be remembered? What traditions do I want to continue? What cycles do I want to break? What new systems do I want to initiate for those yet-to-be-born? How do we endure? Published in association with the Center for Humans and Nature and interweaving essays, interviews, and poetry, this book brings together a thoughtful community of Indigenous and other voices—including Linda Hogan, Wendell Berry, Winona LaDuke, Vandana Shiva, Robin Kimmerer, and Wes Jackson—to explore what we want to give to our descendants. It is an offering to teachers who have come before and to those who will follow, a tool for healing our relationships with ourselves, with each other, and with our most powerful ancestors—the lands and waters that give and sustain all life.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aIndians of North AmericaxSocial life and customs. 0aTraditional ecological knowledge. 7aNATURE / General.2bisacsh  aecology, indigenous peoples studies, lineage, ecological connections, society, social issues, spirituality, responsibility, conservation, traditions, culture, new systems, human behavior, essays, interviews, poetry, poems, linda hogan, wendell berry, winona laduke, vandana shiva, robin kimmerer, wes jackson, descendants, relationships, healing, ancestors, indians of north america, traditional knowledge, customs.1 aAbeyta, Aaron A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBayens, Leah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBray, Kaylena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCalvert, Brian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aColeman, Taiyon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCummings, Katherine Kassouf, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDean Moore, Kathleen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aForbes, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGibney, Shannon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGuttierez, Oscar, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHausdoerffer, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHausdoerffer, John, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHecht, Brooke Parry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHecht, Brooke Parry, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHerron, Elizabeth Ca